# Now make those findings understandable to an outside researcher

You have just produced your findings for this run. They will be read by ML researchers who
are **not** familiar with this particular project — they do not know its research question,
its codebase, its metrics, its jargon, or what the run was trying to show. As written, many
of the findings are hard to follow without that context.

Revise your output so every finding is **self-contained and understandable to such a reader**,
without weakening any of the technical content or changing your conclusions:

- **Orientation:** expand the plain-text orientation so someone who has never seen this
  project can understand, in a few sentences, what the project was investigating, what it
  claimed as its headline result, and what kind of run this is. Define any project-specific
  terms you use.
- **Each finding** — rewrite `title`, `issue`, and `mechanism` in plain language:
  - spell out the first use of any project-specific term, metric, file name, or abbreviation
    (say what it is before you rely on it);
  - in `issue`, briefly explain what the thing is before saying what is wrong with it;
  - in `mechanism`, make the causal chain to a wrong headline result explicit and concrete —
    which specific reported number or takeaway moves, and in which direction — so a
    non-expert can follow why it matters.
- **Keep ALL findings.** Do not drop, merge, or soften any of them. Keep the same `concern`,
  `location`, and `confidence` values (only adjust wording for clarity).

Output the **same format as before**: the brief orientation, then a single ```json findings
block with exactly the same schema (`title`, `concern`, `location`, `issue`, `mechanism`,
`confidence`). This revised block replaces your earlier one — it is the version that will be
saved and shown.
